<subSubSection id="89774C7682510B6CEB6153B2925F5268" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="2B8D6E2176CD53A3ADB27A2D6E92D1C2" pageNumber="661">
<taxonomicName id="DA8928BEBF67C81C6A260AC1E92782E0" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">Proceratium avium Brown</taxonomicName>
, 1974: 71, figs. 1 and 2 (worker, gyne and male). Mauritius: Le Pouce Mt, 700 - 800 m, Native forest, 1 Apr. 1969 (coll. W. L. Brown) [examined] AntWeb MCZTYPE 32216 (MCZC) [de Andrade 2000: 75]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC67C5D2AE9398680DD73E159352DC8B" pageNumber="661">
<taxonomicName id="CDF4AE185E1286C573AA962A7F4A6145" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">Proceratium avioide de Andrade</taxonomicName>
2003: 78, figs 37, 38 (worker, gyne and male). Mauritius: Le Pouce Mt, 700 - 800 m, Native forest, 30 March 1969 (coll. W. L. Brown) [examined] AntWeb MCZTYPE 35017 (MCZC). New synonymy [see justification below]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A45BD43473AC5BAEB20737C72A3095F6" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2F075F8DCE26848AE5079C53E75B847D">
During the trip to Le Pouce on May 25 and 30, seven new collections of 
<taxonomicName id="3E37D7AA37280733D7D8DCC350CF9FE8" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium Roger" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium Roger" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Proceratium</taxonomicName>
from Le Pouce were recorded (Table 2). Because of the small size of the forest patch, only two complete colonies were collected. For the other colonies we encountered, only a few foragers were removed. As Brown (1974) observed, foragers were returning to nests with what appeared to be spider eggs. In this case, they carried the eggs in the mandible, and did not support the eggs with the recurved gaster (Brown 1980). Baroni and de Andrade (2003) suggest the recurved gaster serves a phrag- motic function, but I did not observe the recurved gaster being used to plug up the ant nest entrance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CB9DE06F4713B291A5D8BF2E8A1583C2" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4B91191011CFF7CBE372236A52CB911F" pageNumber="661">
Of note is the fact that colony (BLF 12137) included 352 workers, one ergatoid queen, and no males. Based on the colony size data reported in Baroni and de Adrade (2003), this is the largest colony size recorded for 
<taxonomicName id="EF3030C3BAA1B1CF646C90ECD0F4305D" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium Roger" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Proceratium</taxonomicName>
. Collections in May by Brown in 1969 included males. All nests encountered were located in Nuxia verticillata Lamark (Loganiaceae), with entrances about 1.5 - 2 m above ground. This tree was also the preferred nesting site for 
<taxonomicName id="E4360D4FCFE2B830D839D915799A7B03" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35494" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pristomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bispinosus">Pristomyremx bispinosus</taxonomicName>
. This tree, called bois maigre in Mauritius, has gnarled and twisted trunks. It is endemic to Mauritius and Reunion and appears to be the sole nesting site for 
<taxonomicName id="84DD0BF16FAEDBCC1151850300AC1D21" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35494" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pristomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bispinosus">Pristomyremx bispinosus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="07809676B5B1946B375E85C9A6F00270" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">Proceratium avium</taxonomicName>
. The high winds that are common on Le Pouce abrade the twisted and inter- twined trunks and branches. This action damages the tree at the contact point between intersecting branches and leads to the creation of a rot pocket and nesting site.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3A15BFE7C36178F20B009B7BC526A485" pageNumber="661">
Three collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4D78A72D814368C9DFE4CCA89EBD7CAE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">Proceratium avium</taxonomicName>
(BLF 12011, 12014, and 12139) were foragers follow- ing 
<taxonomicName id="4D8D04A4864C1B758A2DF3498919EE88" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35494" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pristomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bispinosus">Pristomyremx bispinosus</taxonomicName>
. These two species are very similar in color and general appearance. Brown in 1969 also observed this behavior. It is unclear why 
<taxonomicName id="233487A7D2500B67BC36A423B46C4043" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium Roger" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Proceratium</taxonomicName>
is interspersed among the foraging workers of 
<taxonomicName id="3D11E908488BF0FD91A3F5A0232E75A5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35494" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pristomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Pristomyremx bispinosus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bispinosus">P. bispinosus</taxonomicName>
. Conservation of either of these species should include fur- ther investigation of potential beneficial interactions between the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4161233679446FAD4B5D899DAABE8B20" lastPageNumber="663" pageNumber="662">
Justification of Synonymy. - Brown (1980) collected three series of 
<taxonomicName id="B89FCCCE7F06C91857A0DB12E6C2A356" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium Roger" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="662" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Proceratium</taxonomicName>
at Le Pouce in 1969, one on March 30, and two on April 1. The latter were located less than 500 meters from the March 30 collecting site. He described both of these samples as 
<taxonomicName id="BF08DE03CB1F5035FAA364EF318AC851" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="662" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">Proceratium avium</taxonomicName>
(Brown 1974). De Andrade (Baroni Urbani and de Andrade 2003) reexamined these three collec- tions and determined that they represent two species, 
<taxonomicName id="80DC2FC0705EDD48E50CD75094994315" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="662" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2C39835F5DC054D30321F984E276ECEA" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="662" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
. She based this on the observation that 
<taxonomicName id="55AD93D20580E006F12219116027893F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="EBA603BE2C3F5D628502802F0541AA46" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
by the less impressed sculpture, by the denser pilosity, and by longer antennal scapes (
<taxonomicName id="15A74D920D3C7E8E6A67B8AD1F8E354B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
SI 87.3 - 88.6, 
<taxonomicName id="9C5E1A8440A548630E0AA0566742DBAF" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
SI 81.8 - 83.3).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B786A59310F3EA29556493C1D0C61DA9" pageNumber="663">
The measurements of Brown and de Andrade are not consistent, especially for the 
<taxonomicName id="5EA20F6D2C652108DFB13499A91EABAA" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
material she examined. Brown noted measurements for the three collections (workers n = 19) as HL 0.92 - 0.98, HW. 091 - 0.98, CI 96 - 101 SL 0.90 - 0.99. Brown did not calculate SI. De Andrade notes that for her 
<taxonomicName id="7989C854DF899CB3CD45905BC9D33B85" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">avium</taxonomicName>
: HL 1.05 - 1.12, HW. 090 - 0.94, CI 84.5 - 85.7 SL 0.93 - 0.97, SI 87.3 - 88.6 and 
<taxonomicName id="8DC474F645D61A3C4A3BAC7FF186263F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
, HL 1.10 - 1.16, HW. 092 - 0.97, CI 82.1 - 85.1, SL 0.90 - 0.96, SI 81.8 - 83.3. Note that CI for Brown ranged from 96 - 101, while for De Andrade, CI ranged from 82.1 - 85.7.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5C9F32E1D652A28596EBD238E016397" pageNumber="663">
One possible reason for these differences is the differences of HW and SL definitions. Based on the definitions presented above, I re-measured the type material using a calibrated micrometer (see Methods above). Measurements are presented in Table 3. These measurements confirm the rel- ative differences between the Brown collec- tions. However, when samples from the seven new collections are included, these differ- ences become less distinct. The seven collec- tions in the study, have even less impressed sculpture than 
<taxonomicName id="6EFC63CB2AADD6AD9CD38B1C84EFB846" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
, similar pilosity as 
<taxonomicName id="4B955E3A59679F2D1819CE86C81C2BEA" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
, and longer antennal scapes then both 
<taxonomicName id="5547B32F07757DDA2AA782BFC24D1BAF" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CDCD633D26E6EC993DEC78DEE9AD7EA5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avioide De Andrade" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avioide">P. avioide</taxonomicName>
(SI 98 - 103). Based on this study of Brown â€™ s material and the new collections in this study, I identify all these collections as one species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BA3DAE63240D1E16E4FEAD9804CB30CD" pageNumber="663">
The variation observed in these collec- tions is interesting in such a small area. It is possible that because 
<taxonomicName id="26396190BCA7E0026A96279DEF3159D8" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35547" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Proceratium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Proceratium avium Brown" lsidName-HNS="Proceratium avium Brown" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="663" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avium">P. avium</taxonomicName>
has ergatoid queens, and disperses presumably by budding with low dispersal ability, the complex topog- raphy of Le Pouce contributed to the observed variation. The possible restriction of the remaining population to the single forest patch at the base of the southeast peak, however, could severely limit the observed variation in the future.
</paragraph>
